marriage is indissoluble and that a child has the right to be raised, for the

most part, by its mother and father. Amendments were being prepared in 1988

to include the right to an abortion in the constitution and to ensure

non-discrimination in the retraining of women who have lost their jobs, but

high costs, already low birth rate, and lack of education in the general

public concerning family planning would make implementation of such

legislation difficult. The number of abortions in Liechtenstein continues to be

extremely low, fewer than 50 per 1000 live births. The Department of Health

and Social Affairs provides, funds, and maintains six clinics throughout the

country; two are exclusively for women. Pap smears are required of every woman

after her 25th birthday, and then once every 3 years after age 30.

In 1989 the legislature abolished an age limit of abortion and removed the

restriction on the number of children a woman may have. Despite these

changes, abortion is still highly restricted. Generally, abortions are limited

to cases where the life of the woman is in danger, or when the woman has only

dysfunctional uterine bleeding and no organic pathology exists, to save the
